46
00:02:09.698 --> 00:02:14.036
Is that fine? 
Okay, great.

47
00:02:14.036 --> 00:02:18.875
In this presentation, 
I'm going to discuss 

48
00:02:18.875 --> 00:02:21.452
color and contrast
and why it's important

49
00:02:21.452 --> 00:02:24.030
for designers to think
about accessibility

50
00:02:24.030 --> 00:02:27.520
as early as possible
in the design stage,

51
00:02:27.520 --> 00:02:30.720
even at the branding stage,
and I'm going to get into

52
00:02:30.720 --> 00:02:33.850
why many designers,
not just web designers

53
00:02:33.850 --> 00:02:36.950
but designers in general
and developers,

54
00:02:36.950 --> 00:02:40.640
why they're reluctant to
incorporate accessibility

55
00:02:40.640 --> 00:02:43.760
and then who is affected
by our color choices.

56
00:02:43.760 --> 00:02:46.238
And then I'll get into
WCAG guidelines about color

57
00:02:46.238 --> 00:02:48.791
and why accessibility
should be thought about

58
00:02:48.791 --> 00:02:50.641
as early on as
the branding stage

59
00:02:50.641 --> 00:02:53.000
and how accessibility
makes you a better

60
00:02:53.000 --> 00:02:56.160
designer and
problem solver.

61
00:02:56.959 --> 00:02:59.272
A lot of designers
are resistant to

62
00:02:59.272 --> 00:03:01.235
incorporating accessibility 

63
00:03:01.235 --> 00:03:03.508
and I hear 
all kinds of reasons. 

64
00:03:03.508 --> 00:03:06.914
They might think only 
web designers and developers

65
00:03:06.914 --> 00:03:09.519
need to be concerned
with accessibility.

66
00:03:09.519 --> 00:03:12.662
This is probably because
website accessibility lawsuits

67
00:03:12.662 --> 00:03:15.919
have gotten a lot of attention 
over the past few years 

68
00:03:15.919 --> 00:03:19.334
but it does apply to 
a lot more than websites. 

69
00:03:19.334 --> 00:03:22.176
In our industry, 
and with color contrast, 

70
00:03:22.176 --> 00:03:23.961
we're usually talking about

71
00:03:23.961 --> 00:03:27.298
apps, electronic documents,
and then the text,

72
00:03:27.298 --> 00:03:29.233
and the graphics
and interactive elements

73
00:03:29.233 --> 00:03:31.791
that are in them. 

74
00:03:31.791 --> 00:03:33.450
Accessibility is ugly.

75
00:03:33.450 --> 00:03:36.319
I hear this all the time
from designers.

76
00:03:36.319 --> 00:03:38.072
A lot of websites
and designs

77
00:03:38.072 --> 00:03:40.173
are indeed ugly
but they're not ugly

78
00:03:40.173 --> 00:03:43.456
because they're accessible.
They were just poorly designed.

79
00:03:43.456 --> 00:03:45.557
Accessibility has 
nothing to do with 

80
00:03:45.557 --> 00:03:48.015
how visually attractive
a website is,

81
00:03:48.015 --> 00:03:52.400
or a document,
a design, or a graphic.

82
00:03:52.400 --> 00:03:55.920
Accessibility means designing
with only dark colors.

83
00:03:55.920 --> 00:03:59.200
Now I've heard this from
both designers and clients.

84
00:03:59.200 --> 00:04:00.937
In fact, for an email
design project

85
00:04:00.937 --> 00:04:02.720
where a client wanted
the color scheme

86
00:04:02.720 --> 00:04:04.769
to be accessible,
they initially sent us

87
00:04:04.769 --> 00:04:06.310
the color codes
for only their

88
00:04:06.310 --> 00:04:08.044
darker brand colors
which we didn't

89
00:04:08.044 --> 00:04:11.296
find out about until
the middle of the project.

90
00:04:11.296 --> 00:04:13.533
Now here's an
accessible website

91
00:04:13.533 --> 00:04:15.989
I designed and built
several years ago.

92
00:04:15.989 --> 00:04:19.448
It isn't ugly and it doesn't
use dark colors

93
00:04:19.448 --> 00:04:23.196
And here's an example of
using dark colors together

94
00:04:23.196 --> 00:04:25.600
that I found while
shopping online.

95
00:04:25.600 --> 00:04:27.128
People without vision issues 

96
00:04:27.128 --> 00:04:28.866
would have a hard time 
reading this. 

97
00:04:28.866 --> 00:04:30.520
I certainly did.

98
00:04:30.520 --> 00:04:33.472
It always depends on how
the colors are used together,

99
00:04:33.472 --> 00:04:35.130
as I'll get into. 

100
00:04:35.130 --> 00:04:38.395
Some designers and developers,
and their clients,

101
00:04:38.395 --> 00:04:40.836
think that accessibility
only applies to 

102
00:04:40.836 --> 00:04:45.360
a small population
or only to older people.

103
00:04:45.360 --> 00:04:47.598
But worldwide
it is estimated

104
00:04:47.598 --> 00:04:52.479
that 2.2 billion people
have a visual disability.

105
00:04:53.120 --> 00:04:55.058
One of those could be
low vision.

106
00:04:55.058 --> 00:04:58.651
Low vision is having
best corrected visual acuity

107
00:04:58.651 --> 00:05:01.908
at less than 20/40
in the better seeing eye

108
00:05:01.908 --> 00:05:05.559
and this can be due to
macular degeneration,

109
00:05:05.559 --> 00:05:10.118
cataract diabetic retinopathy,
or glaucoma.

110
00:05:10.118 --> 00:05:13.336
Another type of
visual disability

111
00:05:13.336 --> 00:05:15.721
is color blindness
and color blindness

112
00:05:15.721 --> 00:05:18.923
affects eight percent
of males

113
00:05:18.923 --> 00:05:21.919
and half a percent
of females.

114
00:05:22.479 --> 00:05:24.831
Types of color blindness
include

115
00:05:24.831 --> 00:05:26.560
red-green color blindness,

116
00:05:26.560 --> 00:05:28.665
blue-yellow,
and there's even

117
00:05:28.665 --> 00:05:30.560
different types
of each one,

118
00:05:30.560 --> 00:05:34.479
and then there's
complete color blindness.

119
00:05:34.479 --> 00:05:36.639
Some uses of
color and contrast

120
00:05:36.639 --> 00:05:38.800
can actually affect
comprehension

121
00:05:38.800 --> 00:05:41.245
either negatively
or positively,

122
00:05:41.245 --> 00:05:44.772
especially for those
with cognitive, learning,

123
00:05:44.772 --> 00:05:47.073
and neurological disabilities.

124
00:05:47.073 --> 00:05:50.168
Now in the U.S., there's
14.8 million people

125
00:05:50.168 --> 00:05:52.400
who have a
cognitive disability.

126
00:05:52.400 --> 00:05:54.941
Unfortunately, I wasn't able
to find a worldwide number

127
00:05:54.941 --> 00:05:56.183
on that but
as you can see,

128
00:05:56.183 --> 00:05:57.622
these are not
small populations.

129
00:05:57.622 --> 00:06:01.600
These are not small numbers
we're talking about.

130
00:06:02.160 --> 00:06:06.150
Here's another one I hear
from designers and developers,

131
00:06:06.150 --> 00:06:09.318
"My clients don't serve anyone
with a disability."

132
00:06:09.318 --> 00:06:11.775
I actually hear this
from clients too.

133
00:06:11.775 --> 00:06:14.255
You can't see who's 
coming to a website.

134
00:06:14.255 --> 00:06:17.232
You can't see who's reading
your electronic documents.

135
00:06:17.232 --> 00:06:19.459
You might only find out
if somebody complains

136
00:06:19.459 --> 00:06:21.592
that they can't
get around the site,

137
00:06:21.592 --> 00:06:24.080
or they can't access
content in a brochure,

138
00:06:24.080 --> 00:06:27.395
or they can't read something
and they might just

139
00:06:27.395 --> 00:06:30.639
go to a competitor instead.

140
00:06:30.639 --> 00:06:33.159
The Web Content
Accessibility Guidelines,

141
00:06:33.159 --> 00:06:36.469
called WCAG for short,
tell us how to be compliant.

142
00:06:36.469 --> 00:06:39.351
These are internationally
accepted guidelines

143
00:06:39.351 --> 00:06:41.919
and there are three
levels of conformance.

144
00:06:41.919 --> 00:06:45.759
There's A, AA, and AAA
and they range from

145
00:06:45.759 --> 00:06:47.427
minimum to strict. 

146
00:06:47.427 --> 00:06:51.892
The typical level of 
conformance to meet is AA.

147
00:06:51.892 --> 00:06:55.170
AAA is a much
less common request,

148
00:06:55.170 --> 00:06:58.749
so in my presentation
I'm focusing on A and AA,

149
00:06:58.749 --> 00:07:02.639
and focusing on WCAG 2.1.

150
00:07:02.639 --> 00:07:05.600
One of the WCAG guidelines
that deals with color is 

151
00:07:05.600 --> 00:07:08.416
1.4.1 Use of Color,
which says that 

152
00:07:08.416 --> 00:07:11.919
color cannot be the 
only visual means

153
00:07:11.919 --> 00:07:16.261
of conveying information
and that could be text,

154
00:07:16.261 --> 00:07:18.165
that could be 
social media icons, 

155
00:07:18.165 --> 00:07:20.220
for example. 

156
00:07:20.220 --> 00:07:22.411
It could be data graphics. 

157
00:07:22.411 --> 00:07:24.461
In this case, 
the pie chart is 

158
00:07:24.461 --> 00:07:26.960
conveying data on 
each piece of the pie

159
00:07:26.960 --> 00:07:29.573
but it's also conveying
information from

160
00:07:29.573 --> 00:07:33.680
each piece of the pie
to the legend.

161
00:07:33.919 --> 00:07:35.484
Color alone also
cannot be

162
00:07:35.484 --> 00:07:39.260
the only visual means
of indicating an action.

163
00:07:39.260 --> 00:07:42.184
Here's an example
where color alone

164
00:07:42.184 --> 00:07:44.080
is being used
to do that.

165
00:07:44.080 --> 00:07:46.086
Sighted users with
or without a disability

166
00:07:46.086 --> 00:07:49.512
would not be able to tell that 
the word "this" is a hyperlink.

167
00:07:49.512 --> 00:07:52.000
The blue link text
is hardly noticeable

168
00:07:52.000 --> 00:07:54.942
against the surrounding
black body text.

169
00:07:54.942 --> 00:07:57.114
We could assume
it's a hyperlink

170
00:07:57.114 --> 00:08:00.080
but that's if we even notice
the color difference at all,

171
00:08:00.080 --> 00:08:03.280
which most people won't.

172
00:08:03.440 --> 00:08:06.487
Color alone cannot be
the only visual means

173
00:08:06.487 --> 00:08:08.800
of prompting a response.

174
00:08:08.800 --> 00:08:11.900
For example,
a button. 

175
00:08:11.900 --> 00:08:14.000
Color alone cannot be 
the only visual means

176
00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:16.335
of distinguishing
a visual element.

177
00:08:16.335 --> 00:08:18.547
That could be a
form field border

178
00:08:18.547 --> 00:08:20.798
just to show that it's
a form field border

179
00:08:20.798 --> 00:08:22.639
and it could also be
showing a field

180
00:08:22.639 --> 00:08:26.424
that contains
an error as well.

181
00:08:26.424 --> 00:08:29.599
WCAG 1.4.3 Contrast Minimum

182
00:08:29.599 --> 00:08:32.070
says that text
and images of text

183
00:08:32.070 --> 00:08:36.894
have a contrast ratio
of at least 4.5:1

184
00:08:36.894 --> 00:08:38.846
except for large text,

185
00:08:38.846 --> 00:08:41.636
incidental elements, and logos. 

186
00:08:41.636 --> 00:08:45.393
Normal text is defined 
as 14 pt or less, 

187
00:08:45.393 --> 00:08:48.732
or 18.66 px if you're 
working on the web,

188
00:08:48.732 --> 00:08:52.010
or smaller than that
and it needs to meet 

189
00:08:52.010 --> 00:08:54.664
a contrast ratio of
4.5:1 or more

190
00:08:54.664 --> 00:08:57.633
like I just mentioned,
but large text is at least

191
00:08:57.633 --> 00:09:02.637
14 pt or 18.6 px and bold, 

192
00:09:02.637 --> 00:09:07.758
or at least 18 pt or 24 px 
in any weight. 

193
00:09:07.758 --> 00:09:10.205
Typically,
you're going to see

194
00:09:10.205 --> 00:09:13.106
normal-sized text
used for body text

195
00:09:13.106 --> 00:09:17.668
and header and footer text,
photo captions, block quotes,

196
00:09:17.668 --> 00:09:20.914
navigation menus and
hyperlinks, tables

197
00:09:20.914 --> 00:09:24.409
and form fields, buttons,
form instructions,

198
00:09:24.409 --> 00:09:26.274
and error messages. 

199
00:09:26.274 --> 00:09:29.615
Large text will usually 
be used for headings

200
00:09:29.615 --> 00:09:33.341
and sometimes 
block quotes and buttons.

201
00:09:33.341 --> 00:09:36.608
To check contrast,
you simply enter

202
00:09:36.608 --> 00:09:39.219
the hexadecimal codes
for the foreground

203
00:09:39.219 --> 00:09:42.756
and background colors
into a contrast checker,

204
00:09:42.756 --> 00:09:47.120
and in this example I'm using
the WebAIM Contrast Checker,

205
00:09:47.120 --> 00:09:50.399
and then it will give you
the contrast ratio.

206
00:09:50.399 --> 00:09:52.134
With this particular checker, 

207
00:09:52.134 --> 00:09:55.027
you could even click 
the permalink link under that

208
00:09:55.027 --> 00:09:58.089
and then copy the URL
from it in case you want to

209
00:09:58.089 --> 00:10:00.398
show this information
to someone else

210
00:10:00.398 --> 00:10:03.519
or refer back to it later.

211
00:10:03.519 --> 00:10:09.514
WCAG 1.4.11 Non-text Contrast 
says that

212
00:10:09.514 --> 00:10:11.750
user interface components
and their states,

213
00:10:11.750 --> 00:10:15.318
such as focus and hover
and so forth,

214
00:10:15.318 --> 00:10:18.388
and graphical images,
excuse me, objects

215
00:10:18.388 --> 00:10:23.127
have a contrast ratio
of at least 3:1

216
00:10:23.127 --> 00:10:25.624
against adjacent colors. 

217
00:10:25.624 --> 00:10:28.320
This applies to form fields

218
00:10:28.320 --> 00:10:31.380
at their default and at 
other various states.

219
00:10:31.380 --> 00:10:35.436
So it could be a field
in keyboard focus,

220
00:10:35.436 --> 00:10:38.720
and it could be
social media icons.

221
00:10:38.800 --> 00:10:42.079
The WebAIM Contrast Checker
also has a section

222
00:10:42.079 --> 00:10:44.743
for graphical objects
and user interface components,

223
00:10:44.743 --> 00:10:49.130
so it will tell you right there 
if that passed or failed. 

224
00:10:49.130 --> 00:10:52.313
Hyperlinks need to meet 
the same requirements 

225
00:10:52.313 --> 00:10:54.480
as text against 
their background

226
00:10:54.480 --> 00:10:58.000
but if color alone
and no additional styling,

227
00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:00.653
such as an underline,
is being used

228
00:11:00.653 --> 00:11:05.017
then hyperlinks will also
need to have a 3:1 contrast

229
00:11:05.017 --> 00:11:08.560
against the surrounding
text color.

230
00:11:08.720 --> 00:11:11.172
The WebAIM Contrast Checker
also has 

231
00:11:11.172 --> 00:11:13.454
a Link Contrast Checker 
where you 

232
00:11:13.454 --> 00:11:15.785
enter the hexadecimal 
codes for the link 

233
00:11:15.785 --> 00:11:18.172
and the body text 
and the background colors

234
00:11:18.172 --> 00:11:22.880
and then it will tell you
if they pass or fail.

235
00:11:23.279 --> 00:11:27.768
Now there are
no contrast requirements

236
00:11:27.768 --> 00:11:32.431
for logos, images that 
are purely decorative,

237
00:11:32.431 --> 00:11:34.079
and those could be
decorative borders,

238
00:11:34.079 --> 00:11:36.283
they could be
visual dividers,

239
00:11:36.283 --> 00:11:40.320
or icons that
don't convey any meaning.

240
00:11:40.399 --> 00:11:42.850
Inactive user interface
components such as

241
00:11:42.850 --> 00:11:44.800
a button that
doesn't become active

242
00:11:44.800 --> 00:11:49.920
until someone fills out
all the required form fields,

243
00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:54.240
content that is
not visible to anyone,

244
00:11:54.399 --> 00:11:57.817
images that contain
significant other visual content.

245
00:11:57.817 --> 00:12:00.588
So if you have text
that's unimportant

246
00:12:00.588 --> 00:12:02.944
or just happens
to be in an image,

247
00:12:02.944 --> 00:12:05.120
like this street sign
in a photo,

248
00:12:05.120 --> 00:12:08.320
that would not have to
meet a contrast requirement

249
00:12:08.320 --> 00:12:09.874
unless, in this
particular case,

250
00:12:09.874 --> 00:12:11.981
unless we actually
want to use this image

251
00:12:11.981 --> 00:12:15.288
to convey South 2nd Avenue. 

252
00:12:15.288 --> 00:12:17.183
Other examples would be

253
00:12:17.183 --> 00:12:19.021
an image of a
magazine article

254
00:12:19.021 --> 00:12:23.440
that's being used decoratively 
and not meant to actually be read,

255
00:12:23.440 --> 00:12:27.264
and heat maps which
have to use low contrast colors

256
00:12:27.264 --> 00:12:29.013
so that you can see
the page content

257
00:12:29.013 --> 00:12:33.118
beneath the colors
and then screenshots.

258
00:12:33.118 --> 00:12:36.120
Besides checking contrast,
we can check to see

259
00:12:36.120 --> 00:12:40.059
how something would look
to someone with color blindness.

260
00:12:40.059 --> 00:12:42.103
We can check for this
by using

261
00:12:42.103 --> 00:12:45.183
a color blindness simulator
and in this example

262
00:12:45.183 --> 00:12:49.320
I've used the Coblis
Color Blindness Simulator.

263
00:12:49.320 --> 00:12:51.889
I upload a pie chart
and then the

264
00:12:51.889 --> 00:12:55.008
color blindness simulator
shows how this pie chart,

265
00:12:55.008 --> 00:12:58.078
with those particular colors,
would look to people

266
00:12:58.078 --> 00:13:00.316
with varying forms
of color blindness.

267
00:13:00.316 --> 00:13:07.839
You can see there's
quite a few types there.

268
00:13:09.120 --> 00:13:11.774
You can see how
very different

269
00:13:11.774 --> 00:13:14.959
this pie chart would appear
to some people.

270
00:13:14.959 --> 00:13:17.418
In some cases, you could
still make out

271
00:13:17.418 --> 00:13:19.046
the differences in the legend

272
00:13:19.046 --> 00:13:21.136
but with some types
of colorblindness

273
00:13:21.136 --> 00:13:25.315
there isn't much of a difference
between them visually.

274
00:13:25.315 --> 00:13:29.360
Once we find issues
and we've checked for them

275
00:13:29.360 --> 00:13:31.318
how do we resolve them?

276
00:13:31.318 --> 00:13:34.639
There's actually a
few things we can do.

277
00:13:34.639 --> 00:13:37.218
We can increase
the contrast

278
00:13:37.218 --> 00:13:40.399
between the foreground
and background.

279
00:13:40.480 --> 00:13:44.000
In this example, we can
darken the light green

280
00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:46.225
until it has
sufficient contrast

281
00:13:46.225 --> 00:13:48.320
but the change
is really drastic

282
00:13:48.320 --> 00:13:51.302
and this might be undesirable
in the design.

283
00:13:51.302 --> 00:13:53.237
I mean, it would be for me. 
[laughs]

284
00:13:53.237 --> 00:13:54.953
It's actually from my own 
brand color palette 

285
00:13:54.953 --> 00:13:56.799
and it's too dark 
for my taste

286
00:13:56.799 --> 00:13:59.884
and the look
I'm trying to achieve.

287
00:13:59.884 --> 00:14:03.252
In this case, darkening
this particular orange

288
00:14:03.252 --> 00:14:05.760
from a client's 
brand color palette

289
00:14:05.760 --> 00:14:08.245
only slightly gives it
sufficient contrast

290
00:14:08.245 --> 00:14:12.240
and the change
is hardly noticeable.

291
00:14:12.480 --> 00:14:14.281
Here's an example
of a hyperlink

292
00:14:14.281 --> 00:14:16.399
that does not meet
contrast requirements

293
00:14:16.399 --> 00:14:18.266
against the body text color.

294
00:14:18.266 --> 00:14:21.938
The Link Contrast Checker
assesses the hyperlink color

295
00:14:21.938 --> 00:14:25.487
against the background
and the body text colors.

296
00:14:25.487 --> 00:14:28.240
Now the link text
is a different color

297
00:14:28.240 --> 00:14:30.382
but it doesn't
have enough contrast

298
00:14:30.382 --> 00:14:32.526
to distinguish it
from the body text.

299
00:14:32.526 --> 00:14:34.369
So it's not obvious
to some people

300
00:14:34.369 --> 00:14:36.053
that it's a hyperlink. 

301
00:14:36.053 --> 00:14:38.646
In other words, 
it's using color alone, 

302
00:14:38.646 --> 00:14:43.149
not contrast and not styling,
to show that it's a hyperlink.

303
00:14:43.149 --> 00:14:46.740
Now this particular blue
is slightly lighter

304
00:14:46.740 --> 00:14:49.222
and it still meets the
contrast requirements

305
00:14:49.222 --> 00:14:51.509
against the background
and the body text

306
00:14:51.509 --> 00:14:54.675
but it is still a best practice
to underline links

307
00:14:54.675 --> 00:14:58.734
or give them a border-bottom
in the CSS.

308
00:14:58.734 --> 00:15:01.381
Another way to
resolve contrast issues

309
00:15:01.381 --> 00:15:04.480
is to use a
completely different color.

310
00:15:04.480 --> 00:15:07.175
Here the white text on
this orange background

311
00:15:07.175 --> 00:15:09.851
of the button does not
meet contrast requirements

312
00:15:09.851 --> 00:15:11.493
and so we have
several options.

313
00:15:11.493 --> 00:15:14.087
We can change
the background color

314
00:15:14.087 --> 00:15:17.064
to the dark blue,
this is from my color palette

315
00:15:17.064 --> 00:15:19.222
and the blue gives
sufficient contrast

316
00:15:19.222 --> 00:15:21.821
against the white,
and then we could

317
00:15:21.821 --> 00:15:23.891
change the text
to that same blue

318
00:15:23.891 --> 00:15:25.676
which has
sufficient contrast

319
00:15:25.676 --> 00:15:28.472
against the orange as well,
or we can even

320
00:15:28.472 --> 00:15:31.279
reverse those colors.

321
00:15:31.279 --> 00:15:33.600
Now here with these
form field borders,

322
00:15:33.600 --> 00:15:35.088
the orange does not have

323
00:15:35.088 --> 00:15:37.226
enough contrast
with the background.

324
00:15:37.226 --> 00:15:38.959
Instead of darkening it though,

325
00:15:38.959 --> 00:15:40.300
we could choose
another color

326
00:15:40.300 --> 00:15:41.935
from the brand color palette

327
00:15:41.935 --> 00:15:45.012
that does have
sufficient contrast.

328
00:15:45.012 --> 00:15:47.839
In this example with
social media icons,

329
00:15:47.839 --> 00:15:51.040
these are really light so
we could choose another color

330
00:15:51.040 --> 00:15:53.991
from the client's color palette. 

331
00:15:53.991 --> 00:15:56.048
Now with some elements,

332
00:15:56.048 --> 00:15:59.383
we can use styling
to differentiate them.

333
00:15:59.383 --> 00:16:02.248
Going back to
the hyperlink example,

334
00:16:02.248 --> 00:16:05.217
if the link text has
sufficient contrast

335
00:16:05.217 --> 00:16:07.527
with the background,
then instead of using

336
00:16:07.527 --> 00:16:11.112
contrast to distinguish it
from the surrounding body text

337
00:16:11.112 --> 00:16:13.123
we could simply
add an underline

338
00:16:13.123 --> 00:16:15.753
or a border-bottom style.

339
00:16:15.753 --> 00:16:19.120
Or we can add
a background color.

340
00:16:19.120 --> 00:16:22.120
We could also add
a background color

341
00:16:22.120 --> 00:16:25.199
to show a field
that is in focus.

342
00:16:25.199 --> 00:16:27.988
To show form fields
that have an error,

343
00:16:27.988 --> 00:16:30.079
we could use
a thicker outline

344
00:16:30.079 --> 00:16:32.032
and/or one that's
in a different color

345
00:16:32.032 --> 00:16:34.665
that has sufficient contrast
with the background

346
00:16:34.665 --> 00:16:38.639
and the field border
default state.

347
00:16:38.639 --> 00:16:40.970
Now let's talk about
how the accessibility

348
00:16:40.970 --> 00:16:42.997
of our color choices
can affect branding

349
00:16:42.997 --> 00:16:45.074
and why accessibility
should be brought up

350
00:16:45.074 --> 00:16:49.360
as early as possible even
at the branding stage.

351
00:16:49.360 --> 00:16:52.442
Number one is that
the visual brand integrity

352
00:16:52.442 --> 00:16:55.114
can be affected. 

353
00:16:55.114 --> 00:16:57.670
Now here's an example of that.

354
00:16:57.670 --> 00:17:00.455
This is the branding
of my client-based business

355
00:17:00.455 --> 00:17:05.363
and it uses a light green
and gray as the two main colors.

356
00:17:05.363 --> 00:17:06.635
Purple is what
I want to be

357
00:17:06.635 --> 00:17:08.976
more of an accent color.
I developed these colors

358
00:17:08.976 --> 00:17:10.761
before I got into accessibility

359
00:17:10.761 --> 00:17:12.571
and was even
aware of accessibility,

360
00:17:12.571 --> 00:17:14.877
so, [brief laugh] this is all 
happening after the fact.

361
00:17:14.877 --> 00:17:17.291
So, it would have to be
a much different

362
00:17:17.291 --> 00:17:19.275
darker hue of green
as I showed earlier,

363
00:17:19.275 --> 00:17:22.054
like an army green,
and that would change

364
00:17:22.054 --> 00:17:24.206
my brand color palette
and the brighter look

365
00:17:24.206 --> 00:17:26.880
that I want to have.

366
00:17:26.880 --> 00:17:28.686
You might also
need to weigh

367
00:17:28.686 --> 00:17:32.069
whether or not the design
will end up being too heavy

368
00:17:32.069 --> 00:17:34.837
on one color, which
you may not want.

369
00:17:34.837 --> 00:17:37.475
In this case, in order to
meet contrast requirements,

370
00:17:37.475 --> 00:17:39.222
in certain places
I've had to change

371
00:17:39.222 --> 00:17:42.683
the gray to purple. 

372
00:17:42.683 --> 00:17:44.333
I don't care for 
having so much purple. 

373
00:17:44.333 --> 00:17:48.071
It's more prominent 
than my primary brand colors 

374
00:17:48.071 --> 00:17:51.360
but it does give a warmer feel.

375
00:17:51.360 --> 00:17:53.561
Something to consider
with your work is

376
00:17:53.561 --> 00:17:56.493
how will brand recognition
be affected if you end up

377
00:17:56.493 --> 00:17:58.880
needing to use more
of the secondary colors

378
00:17:58.880 --> 00:18:01.907
rather than the primary ones
or having to darken

379
00:18:01.907 --> 00:18:04.047
a client's primary color palette?

380
00:18:04.047 --> 00:18:06.640
Plus, you don't want
the client's website

381
00:18:06.640 --> 00:18:09.722
to be accessible with
a modified color palette

382
00:18:09.722 --> 00:18:12.474
but then their other materials
use the original

383
00:18:12.474 --> 00:18:14.728
non-accessible color palette. 

384
00:18:14.728 --> 00:18:18.000
It's really important 
that they're consistent.

385
00:18:18.240 --> 00:18:21.607
It is much more costly
to remediate websites

386
00:18:21.607 --> 00:18:23.913
and documents
and color palettes

387
00:18:23.913 --> 00:18:25.913
after the fact,
when accessibility

388
00:18:25.913 --> 00:18:27.544
is an afterthought. 

389
00:18:27.544 --> 00:18:29.119
That's not just 
a financial cost 

390
00:18:29.119 --> 00:18:32.000
but also the cost of 
brand recognition.

391
00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:34.464
Will your client 
lose business as a result, 

392
00:18:34.464 --> 00:18:36.088
because some 
people may not 

393
00:18:36.088 --> 00:18:38.551
immediately recognize 
the branding anymore 

394
00:18:38.551 --> 00:18:40.696
once these changes 
have been made. 

395
00:18:40.696 --> 00:18:43.955
Color plays a big part 
in brand recognition. 

396
00:18:43.955 --> 00:18:45.549
Think about McDonald's.

397
00:18:45.549 --> 00:18:49.219
What if the Golden Arches
were changed to green?

398
00:18:49.219 --> 00:18:52.969
Often when I'm remediating
InDesign files for accessibility,

399
00:18:52.969 --> 00:18:55.875
I have to modify the client's
color palette.

400
00:18:55.875 --> 00:18:59.039
In this case, I was provided
a fully designed file

401
00:18:59.039 --> 00:19:02.093
which needed to be
made accessible

402
00:19:02.093 --> 00:19:03.986
after the fact,
and so you can see here

403
00:19:03.986 --> 00:19:06.168
how changing the light green
to an army green

404
00:19:06.168 --> 00:19:08.960
looks drastically different.
It gives a different effect.

405
00:19:08.960 --> 00:19:11.457
So, again, this is definitely
something to consider

406
00:19:11.457 --> 00:19:14.253
in the beginning
with brand identity design,

407
00:19:14.253 --> 00:19:17.177
and sometimes it's a case
of needing to rework

408
00:19:17.177 --> 00:19:19.721
the design with
different colors,

409
00:19:19.721 --> 00:19:22.129
and sometimes
the design itself,

410
00:19:22.129 --> 00:19:24.782
keeping the existing colors
but changing

411
00:19:24.782 --> 00:19:27.478
how they're used,
needs to be done.

412
00:19:27.478 --> 00:19:30.108
In this case,
I changed the design

413
00:19:30.108 --> 00:19:32.230
to use the light green
against the purple

414
00:19:32.230 --> 00:19:35.138
and then I used the orange
in a decorative way.

415
00:19:35.138 --> 00:19:37.580
Changing the design
after the fact is costly

416
00:19:37.580 --> 00:19:39.214
and time consuming
to the client

417
00:19:39.214 --> 00:19:41.469
because accessibility
was an afterthought.

418
00:19:41.469 --> 00:19:43.745
In these situations
you're revisiting

419
00:19:43.745 --> 00:19:45.401
the design process
a second time

420
00:19:45.401 --> 00:19:47.715
so it's almost like
the client's paying

421
00:19:47.715 --> 00:19:50.706
for the design work twice
and it requires the client

422
00:19:50.706 --> 00:19:54.231
to review the new look
which adds additional time

423
00:19:54.231 --> 00:19:56.720
that they probably
hadn't planned on.

424
00:19:56.720 --> 00:19:59.605
Accessibility can affect
an organization's brand values

425
00:19:59.605 --> 00:20:04.400
and experience and this
can work for or against them.

426
00:20:04.400 --> 00:20:07.098
Implementing accessibility is
the right thing to do

427
00:20:07.098 --> 00:20:09.869
and it leaves
a positive impression.

428
00:20:09.869 --> 00:20:12.640
It gives a business
a good reputation.

429
00:20:12.640 --> 00:20:14.554
When accessibility
is ignored, though,

430
00:20:14.554 --> 00:20:16.720
it gives the business
a negative reputation

431
00:20:16.720 --> 00:20:19.564
on diversity and people
with a disability

432
00:20:19.564 --> 00:20:22.038
are three times as likely
to avoid that business

433
00:20:22.038 --> 00:20:24.650
and twice as likely to
dissuade others

434
00:20:24.650 --> 00:20:26.479
from doing business with it.

435
00:20:26.479 --> 00:20:28.960
Accessibility can be
good for business.

436
00:20:28.960 --> 00:20:32.112
71% of users with a disability
leave a website

437
00:20:32.112 --> 00:20:33.889
that is not accessible. 

438
00:20:33.889 --> 00:20:37.152
Color only plays 
one part in that, of course

439
00:20:37.152 --> 00:20:40.372
but consider how having
an inaccessible website

440
00:20:40.372 --> 00:20:42.960
might be potentially
costing your client.

441
00:20:42.960 --> 00:20:46.177
For example, a young woman
with low vision is looking for 

442
00:20:46.177 --> 00:20:48.363
pregnancy support 
on a website. 

443
00:20:48.363 --> 00:20:50.880
The headings are in 
baby blue and pink

444
00:20:50.880 --> 00:20:52.636
and she has a hard time
reading them

445
00:20:52.636 --> 00:20:55.348
because they're too light
against the white background.

446
00:20:55.348 --> 00:20:57.829
So she leaves
and goes to another site.

447
00:20:57.829 --> 00:20:59.621
A male user
with color blindness

448
00:20:59.621 --> 00:21:01.908
is shopping for a gift
for his wife online

449
00:21:01.908 --> 00:21:04.451
but he's unable to 
make out the hyperlinks

450
00:21:04.451 --> 00:21:05.914
that go to the products. 

451
00:21:05.914 --> 00:21:08.685
He leaves and goes to 
a competitor's site.

452
00:21:08.685 --> 00:21:11.293
A legally blind woman
wants to make a donation

453
00:21:11.293 --> 00:21:13.809
to an animal rescue
but finds it hard to read

454
00:21:13.809 --> 00:21:16.729
the small light gray text
on the website.

455
00:21:16.729 --> 00:21:19.349
She doesn't use a screen reader

456
00:21:19.349 --> 00:21:23.360
and she doesn't know
that she can adjust contrast

457
00:21:23.360 --> 00:21:26.976
or text size in the browser
on her operating system

458
00:21:26.976 --> 00:21:31.040
and so she leaves the site
feeling frustrated.

459
00:21:31.040 --> 00:21:34.727
Accessibility provides a
better experience for all users.

460
00:21:34.727 --> 00:21:37.691
Most people won't notice
that something is accessible

461
00:21:37.691 --> 00:21:39.760
but they will appreciate
the benefits.

462
00:21:39.760 --> 00:21:44.000
In terms of color and contrast
that means enhanced readability,

463
00:21:44.000 --> 00:21:47.100
and clearly distinguishable
hyperlinks

464
00:21:47.100 --> 00:21:49.115
and interface components. 

465
00:21:49.115 --> 00:21:51.596
Here is a horrendous example

466
00:21:51.596 --> 00:21:54.170
and I was shocked
to have found this

467
00:21:54.170 --> 00:21:56.880
on a county website [laughs],
a government website.

468
00:21:56.880 --> 00:21:59.043
Users without
a visual disability

469
00:21:59.043 --> 00:22:01.039
cannot read this
white on white text

470
00:22:01.039 --> 00:22:03.100
and even with
the drop shadow

471
00:22:03.100 --> 00:22:06.159
the text fails to appear
and I guess they want

472
00:22:06.159 --> 00:22:07.872
you to too [laughs]. 

473
00:22:07.872 --> 00:22:10.320
Again, all users 
would benefit

474
00:22:10.320 --> 00:22:13.763
from this content
being made accessible.

475
00:22:13.763 --> 00:22:15.401
Remember this?

476
00:22:15.401 --> 00:22:20.559
Users without vision issues
would have trouble reading this.

477
00:22:20.559 --> 00:22:24.000
These form fields would be
hard for most users to see,

478
00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:29.280
or to read, or to know where
to input their information.

479
00:22:29.280 --> 00:22:31.978
Here's an example again
with the hyperlink.

480
00:22:31.978 --> 00:22:33.969
Some sighted users 
and users with a visual 

481
00:22:33.969 --> 00:22:36.432
or cognitive disability 
would not be able 

482
00:22:36.432 --> 00:22:38.035
to tell this is a hyperlink.

483
00:22:38.035 --> 00:22:41.380
The blue link text
is hardly noticeable

484
00:22:41.380 --> 00:22:43.766
against the black text
and we could assume

485
00:22:43.766 --> 00:22:46.875
it's a hyperlink if we even
notice the color difference

486
00:22:46.875 --> 00:22:52.182
but again, most people won't.
But just don't make people think.

487
00:22:52.182 --> 00:22:58.101
97% of the top 1 million websites
fail a basic test for accessibility.

488
00:22:58.101 --> 00:22:59.819
Having a more accessible website

489
00:22:59.819 --> 00:23:02.262
could give your clients
a competitive edge

490
00:23:02.262 --> 00:23:04.558
and it also gives you
a competitive edge

491
00:23:04.558 --> 00:23:06.650
because most designers
and developers

492
00:23:06.650 --> 00:23:08.420
don't bring this up
and you'd be

493
00:23:08.420 --> 00:23:10.501
the one informing them
about it.

494
00:23:10.501 --> 00:23:12.899
Addressing accessibility
can make you

495
00:23:12.899 --> 00:23:15.423
a better designer
and problem solver

496
00:23:15.423 --> 00:23:18.301
because design is not about
just looking good.

497
00:23:18.301 --> 00:23:21.730
It's all about communication
and it will add more value

498
00:23:21.730 --> 00:23:24.942
to your branding
and design work.

499
00:23:24.942 --> 00:23:28.720
Let's recap some
key points here.

500
00:23:28.720 --> 00:23:33.163
Don't use color alone
to convey information.

501
00:23:33.163 --> 00:23:37.064
Sufficient contrast
is good for everyone.

502
00:23:37.064 --> 00:23:40.311
Check color contrast
of any elements

503
00:23:40.311 --> 00:23:42.144
that are conveying
information.

504
00:23:42.144 --> 00:23:45.755
Your normal text
is going to be 4.5:1

505
00:23:45.755 --> 00:23:48.720
and large text 3:1.

506
00:23:48.720 --> 00:23:52.320
The checker I mentioned was
the WebAIM Contrast Checker

507
00:23:52.320 --> 00:23:55.158
and The Paciello Group
also has one that's called

508
